The '''Aryan Games''' ({{lang-de|Arische Spiele}}<ref name=Rusinek>{{cite book |author=Bernd A. Rusinek |chapter=Der Kult der Jugend und des Krieges |chapterurl={{Google books|5_9nAAAAMAAJ|keywords="arische Spiele"|plainurl=y}} |editor1=Jost Dülffer |editor2=Gerd Krumeich |title=Der verlorene Frieden: Politik und Kriegskultur nach 1918 (Bibliothek für Zeitgeschichte, Band 15) |publisher=Klartext |location=Essen |year=2002 |page=181 |isbn=978-3-89861-075-9 |language=de}}</ref>) were a proposed replacement for the [[Olympic Games]] in the [[Third Reich]]. Proposed by [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] sports organizer [[Carl Diem]] and subsequently adopted by [[Adolf Hitler]], these [[Multi-sport event|multi-sport games]] were supposed to be housed permanently in [[Nuremberg]] at the planned "[[Deutsches Stadion|German Stadium]]", that had been designed by Nazi architect [[Albert Speer]], but was never built.
The idea was originally entertained in 1939 by Carl Diem, chief organiser of the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] in Berlin, who ahead of the 1936 Olympics was already noted for claiming that "[[Germanic peoples|Germanics]] may only be defeated by other Germanics," which turned out not to be the case.<ref name=Rusinek /> The idea was subsequently adopted by Hitler, who told Albert Speer that once the German Stadium was built, there would be no more Olympic Games, only the Aryan Games.<ref> Kruger, Arnd and William Murray. The Nazi Olympics: Sport, Politics, and Appeasement in the 1930s. Urbana: University of Illinois Press, c2003. 260 pages. UCSB Main Library GV722 1936 .N39 2003 </ref><ref>[http://www.history.ucsb.edu/faculty/marcuse/classes/133d/essays/Mandell1971Saucedo083.htm “Hitler’s Secret Weapon: Propaganda Through Athletics”:]</ref>
==See also== * [[Aryan race]]
