{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} '''Good Friday processions in Baliuag''' or '''Holy Week procession in [[Baliuag, Bulacan]]''' is an event taking place in [[Holy Week]], in a traditional Roman Catholic culture of the [[St. Augustine Parish Church of Baliuag]].
In the [[Philippines]], [[Good Friday]]<ref group="nb">The etymology of the term "good" in the context of Good Friday is contested. Some sources claim it is from the senses ''pious'', ''holy'' of the word "good",</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourdictionary.com/good-friday |title=Good Friday &#124; Easy to understand definition of Good Friday by Your Dictionary |publisher=Yourdictionary.com |date=17 April 2013}}</ref> while others contend that it is a corruption of "[[God in Christianity|God]] Friday".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06643a.htm |title=Catholic Encyclopedia: Good Friday |publisher=Newadvent.org |date=1 September 1909}}</ref> is a [[religious holiday]] observed primarily by Christians commemorating the [[crucifixion of Jesus Christ]] and his death at [[Calvary]]. The holiday is observed during [[Holy Week]] as part of the [[Paschal Triduum]] on the Friday preceding [[Easter Sunday]], and may coincide with the Jewish observance of [[Passover]]. It is also known as '''Holy Friday''', '''Great Friday''', '''Black Friday''',<ref> *{{cite book|title=The Chambers Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pz2ORay2HWoC&pg=RA1-PA639|accessdate=13 April 2012|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-86062-25-8|page=639}} *{{cite book|author1=Elizabeth Webber|author2=Mike Feinsilber|title=Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of Allusions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ACB81ZeNN5sC&pg=PA67|accessdate=13 April 2012|year=1999|publisher=Merriam-Webster|isbn=978-0-87779-628-2|page=67}} *{{cite book|author1=Franklin M. Segler|author2=Randall Bradley|title=Christian Worship: Its Theology And Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fSRHbo_RfLoC&pg=PA226|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=1 October 2006|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8054-4067-6|page=226}}</ref> or '''Easter Friday''',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bainger|first=Fleur|title=Fish frenzy for Easter Friday|url=http://www.abc.net.au/rural/wa/content/2010/04/s2862913.htm|accessdate=22 April 2011|newspaper=[[ABC Online]]|date=1 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hamilton-Irvine|first=Gary|title=Relax Easter trading laws for Rotorua, say retailers|url=http://www.rotoruadailypost.co.nz/news/relax-easter-trading-laws-for-rotorua-say-retailer/1811749/|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=[[Rotorua Daily Post]]|date=30 March 2013}}</ref><ref>"[http://store.emumusic.com.au/index.php?page=shop.product_details&flypage=flypage.tpl&product_id=333&category_id=23&option=com_virtuemart&Itemid=15&vmcchk=1&Itemid=15 Easter Friday]" by Simone Richardson, 2006. Published by Emu Music.</ref> though the latter properly refers to the [[Easter Friday|Friday in Easter week]]. [[File:GoodFridayprocessionsinBaliuagjf2001 05.JPG|thumb|Photo of 1 of the 96 floats (carrozas-carriages of Holy Images, 29 March 2013 [[Good Friday]] procession in [[Baliuag, Bulacan]].]]
Baliuag Good Friday processions like any other religious [[processions]] are found in almost every form of Christian and Catholic worship, such as [[Holy Week]] processions. Some biblical examples were the processions with the [[Ark of Covenant]] and the procession of [[Jesus on a donkey]] into Jerusalem.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Processions}}</ref>
==Carrozas== In [[Baliuag, Bulacan]], the 2013 "Prusisyon ng mga Santo" was the Lenten rite wherein 96 carrozas participated compared to some 83 religious images that were paraded through the streets in the previous years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Visitmyphilippines.com |url=http://www.visitmyphilippines.com/index.php?title=Bulacan&func=all&pid=4526 |title=Department of Tourism – The Philippines Ultimate Travel Guide for Tourist |publisher=Visitmyphilippines.com |date=}}</ref> In the Lenten [[procession]], religious fervor and piety compelled the town people of Baliuag to launch over a hundred richly adorned giant floats depicting the passion of Jesus Christ.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/article.php?aid=5444&sid=1&subid=1#.UVWuvaIrSVY |title=Time-tested rites on Good Friday |publisher=Mb.com.ph |date=29 March 2013}}</ref>
Held every Holy Wednesday and Good Friday, the procession starts at 6:00 in the Evening.<ref>{{cite web|author=Manila Bulletin&nbsp;–&nbsp;Thu, 21 April 2011 |url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/good-friday-traditions-solemn-rites-held-today-082220048.html |title=Good Friday traditions, solemn rites held today – Yahoo! News Philippines |publisher=Ph.news.yahoo.com |date=21 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/article.php?aid=5223&sid=1&subid=1 |title=Holy Wednesday Focuses on Judas’ Betrayal of Jesus |publisher=Mb.com.ph |date=27 March 2013 }}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The grand procession of more than 80 images became an anticipated attraction on Holy Wednesday and Good Friday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivanhenares.com/2010/04/bulacan-holy-wednesday-and-good-friday.html |title=Bulacan: Holy Wednesday and Good Friday processions in Baliuag, Bulacan &#124; Ivan About Town &#124; Tourist Spots in the Philippines &#124; Philippine Travel Blog |publisher=Ivanhenares.com |date=2 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/article.php?aid=5444&sid=1&subid=1#.UVWuvaIrSVY |title=Time-tested rites on Good Friday |publisher=Mb.com.ph |date=29 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.panda.org/coral_triangle/2010/04/26/good-friday-in-bulacan-philippines/ |title=Good Friday in Bulacan, Philippines &#124; WWF Coral Triangle Photo Expedition |publisher=Blogs.panda.org |date=26 April 2010}}</ref>
The 2013 Good Friday 96 massive carriages carrying life size dioramas depicting a scene in the life of Jesus were paraded all over town after sunset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tempo.com.ph/2013/03/solemn-rites-on-good-friday/#.UVWtR6IrSVY |title=Solemn rites on Good Friday &#124; Tempo – News in a Flash |publisher=Tempo |date=29 March 2013}}</ref> The solemn rite on Good Friday,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulacan.gov.ph/tourism/touristspot.php?id=86 |title=Bulacan, Philippines: Tourism: Baliuag Lenten Procession, Baliuag, Bulacan |publisher=Bulacan.gov.ph |date=}}</ref> called the Baliuag Lenten Procession<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/video/nation/regions/04/07/12/tourists-witness-good-friday-procession-baliwag |title=Tourists witness Good Friday procession in Baliwag |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=}}</ref> was witnessed by local and foreign tourists, including the current [[Apostolic Nunciature to the Philippines]]' Apostolic Nuncio Archbishop Giuseppe Pinto who was accompanied by his aide Msgr. Gabor Pinter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thedailyguardian.net/index.php/local-news/7768-archbishop-giuseppe-pinto |title=Archbishop Giuseppe Pinto |publisher=Thedailyguardian.net |date=13 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220122426/http://thedailyguardian.net/index.php/local-news/7768-archbishop-giuseppe-pinto |archivedate=20 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bpint|Archbishop Giuseppe Pinto|23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Esperas |first=Raoul |url=http://mnnetherlands.com/dir/_page/101327/ |title=New Papal Nuncio Giuseppe Pinto arrives in Manila |publisher=Mnnetherlands.com |date= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130411092926/http://mnnetherlands.com/dir/_page/101327/ |archivedate=11 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traveltothephilippines.info/2012/07/29/the-magnificent-baliuag-lenten-holy-week-procession-in-bulacan/ |title=The Magnificent Baliuag Lenten (Hoy Week) Procession in Bulacan |publisher=Traveltothephilippines.info |date=}}</ref>
It is the longest Lenten procession in the Philippines, followed by the Holy Week Procession from the San Isidro Labrador Parish from the nearby town of Pulilan. The 96 Baliuag ([[St. Augustine Parish Church of Baliuag]]) floats showcased the grand parade of lavishly decorated carriages which event culminated in the blessing with holy water of the floats and the faithful by 2 Baliuag Priests from the Team Ministry of the [[Diocese of Malolos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dragonflycollector.com/2012/04/06/larger-than-life-on-good-friday/ |title=Larger Than Life on Good Friday &#124; Musings of a Commoner |publisher=Dragonflycollector.com |date=7 April 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://96.31.84.32/articles/201873/passion-christ-processions-today#.UVWu6qIrSVY]</ref> Passion<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.breakingnews.ph/158541/tourists-witness-good-friday-procession-baliwag |title=Tourists witness Good Friday procession in Baliwag &#124; Breaking News Philippines |publisher=Breakingnews.ph |date=}}</ref>
This year 2017 Holy Week Procession, the carrozas has an approximate of 117 carrozas compare last year, the carrozas has a numbered of 114 carrozas only; This is much higher than last year 2016 holy week procession.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAaIVOfcsFY</ref> In 2018, only 1 carroza was added, making the total number of carrozas to 118.
==Cultural references== Good Friday assumes a particular importance in the plot of [[Richard Wagner]]'s music drama ''[[Parsifal]]'', which contains an orchestral interlude known as the "Good Friday Music".
