==Aftermath==

===Trial===
The court case following the "Milperra Massacre" was at the time one of the largest in Australian history.{{sfn|BBC News|1984}} In total 43 people were originally charged with seven counts of murder under the doctrine of "[[common purpose]]"{{sfn|BBC News|1984}} however, charges against 10 were dropped before trial and Bernard "Bernie" Podgorski, secretary of the Bandidos, was granted immunity after turning [[Turn state's evidence|Queen's Evidence]].{{sfn|Morton|Lobez|2010|p=book pages are un-numbered:alphabetical listing of topics}}
[[Solicitor]] Christopher Murphy acted for the Bandidos' members charged as a result of the incident. [[Greg James (judge)|Greg James QC]], as he then was, represented all but one of the Bandidos' members during their trial, that being Colin Campbell. Greg James QC was Juniored by a number of Juniors including John Korn, Kenneth Rosin, Andrew Martin, and Philip Young. Mr. Campbell was represented by Mr [[Greg Woods]] QC, as he then was. Anthony "Snoddy" Spencer, the Bandidos National President, hanged himself in prison before he could stand trial.

During the longest joint criminal trial in New South Wales history,{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} 58 policemen provided security including armed members of the [[State Protection Group|Tactical Operations Unit]] who were stationed in the courtroom and witnesses required armed guards from the [[State Protection Group|Witness Security Unit]] to escort them home. With 31 accused, each by law able to reject 20 jurors without giving a reason, 1,500 jurors were called up and housed at the [[Penrith Panthers|Penrith Leagues Club]] to await selection. The first day of selection saw only five jurors accepted from 208 presented, the following day it was found that two were ineligible with justice Roden dismissing all five and ordering that jury selection begin again. Eventually some 1,000 jurors were presented before 12 were found acceptable to sit on the case.  More than two years later, on 12 June 1987, the jury delivered 63 murder convictions, 147 manslaughter convictions and 31 of affray. The judge in the case named the instigator of the violence as William "Jock" Ross, the "supreme commander" of the Comancheros, saying "Ross was primarily responsible for the decision that members of his club go to Milperra in force and armed".{{sfn|BBC News|1984}}

Ross received a life sentence for his role in the violence. Four other members of the Comancheros gang received life sentences for murder and 16 Bandidos received sentences of seven years for manslaughter. As the Bandidos arrested were charged in regards to all the deaths, this resulted in Colin Campbell being found guilty of the manslaughter of his own brother. Another Campbell brother, John "Wack" Campbell, died three years later from the injuries he received that day.  [[Commonwealth Games]] gold medallist boxer [[Philip McElwaine|Philip "Knuckles" McElwaine]] was found guilty only of affray, he was the only motorcycle club member to be acquitted of the manslaughter and murder charges that were brought against him.{{sfn|Simpson|Harvey|1989|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2012}}{{efn|McElwaine was a volunteer at the [[Police and Community Youth Club]] and police acted as character witnesses for him, stating that he was "a monument to the police boys' movement as a whole"{{sfn|Simpson|1986|p=5}}}} In 1989, three Comancheros successfully appealed their murder convictions with the charge quashed and reduced to manslaughter. In 1992, Ross was the last to be released after serving five years and three months.{{sfn|Morton|Lobez|2010|p=book pages are un-numbered:alphabetical listing of topics}}

===Changes to gun laws===
The Comancheros were notorious for carrying registered shotguns openly while riding.{{sfn|Brown|2001}} As a result of the [[massacre]], the ''New South Wales Firearms and Dangerous Weapons Act 1973'', which allowed registered owners the right to carry firearms in public, was subsequently amended to require "a good reason for the issue of a [firearm] licence".{{sfn|NSW Police Force}}{{efn|For example, rural landholders, members of an approved gun club and persons engaged in lawful business involving the use of firearms were deemed to have a good reason and the police could refuse to issue licences to any persons they saw as not having a good reason.}}

===Resumption of hostilities===
In a repetition of the circumstances that led to the Milperra massacre, in early 2007 more than 60 members of the [[Parramatta]] and [[Granville, New South Wales|Granville]] chapters of the [[Nomads (motorcycle club)|Nomads]], previously affiliated with the Comancheros, defected to the Bandidos. The defection resulted in a new eruption of violence between the Comancheros and Bandidos involving fire-bombings and drive-by shootings.{{sfn|Kennedy|2009}} [[New South Wales Police]] set up Operation Ranmore to stop the violence escalating, which resulted in 340 people arrested on 883 charges as of January 2008.{{sfn|Brisbane Times|2008}}

==Dramatisation==
In 2002, Australian film maker [[Martin Brown (producer)|Martin Brown]] produced a documentary titled "1% One Percenters Search For A Screenplay" in an effort to raise interest for a big budget movie of the massacre. The documentary, first aired on 2 February 2003, follows Brown as he looks for screenwriters, funds and a director for his movie. It includes interviews with the police investigating officer, ex superintendent Ron Stephenson, Comanchero president "Jock" Ross, Bandido vice president "Bullets" and several other Milperra survivors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200502/highlights/248780.htm|date=2 February 2011|title=1% One Percenters Search For A Screenplay|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC)}}</ref>

A television mini-series ''[[Bikie Wars: Brothers in Arms]]'', based on the book ''Brothers in Arms'' by  Lindsay Simpson and Sandra Harvey, screened on Australias  [[Network Ten]] in May 2012. The screenplay was written by [[Greg Haddrick]], Roger Simpson and Jo Martino. It is directed by Peter Andrikidis.{{sfn|Knox|2011}} It stars [[Callan Mulvey]], [[Matthew Nable]], [[Susie Porter]], [[Maeve Dermody]], [[Anthony Hayes (actor)|Anthony Hayes]], [[Todd Lasance]], [[Luke Ford (actor)|Luke Ford]], [[Jeremy Lindsay Taylor]], [[Damian Walshe-Howling]], [[Nathaniel Dean]] and [[Luke Hemsworth]].  Colin "Caesar" Campbell has criticized the series for a lack of consultation with those who were there, its incorrect chronology of events, errors in motives and the portrayal of "lazy stereotypes".{{sfn|Gridneff|2012}}

