{{Multiple issues| {{primary sources|date=October 2015}} {{unreliable sources|date=October 2015}} {{POV|date=October 2015}} {{weasel|date=October 2015}} {{Underlinked|date=August 2016}} }}
{{Infobox Convention | name = Seybold Seminars | image = | caption = | status = Inactive | genre = publishing conference and trade show | venue = | location = | country = United States | first = 1981 | last = 2005 | organizer = | filing = | attendance = | website = }}
'''Seybold Seminars''' was a leading seminar and "the premier trade show for the desktop publishing and pre-press industry."<ref>{{cite news| first = Charles| last = Piller| title = The Web and the Future of Desktop Publishing| work = Los Angeles Times| date = 1996-09-23| accessdate = 2010-09-14| url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-23/business/fi-46769_1_desktop-publishing}}</ref> It was founded in 1981 by Jonathan Seybold, son of the printing innovator [[John W. Seybold]], and complemented Seybold Publications, a branch of the Seybold business that was known for its influential ''Seybold Report'' newsletters.
Seybold Seminars focused on electronic publishing, printing and graphics. Its biannual events covered the industry in rapid transformation by computing technology and created a forum for theoretical discussion as well as practical applications of that technology. Initially focusing on the issues surrounding computers delivering images and text to print, the Seminars came to deal with a much wider range of new issues and technology as publishers embraced multimedia, online publishing, and rapid advances in color technology.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Seybold San Francisco '94| work = Newsbytes| location = San Francisco| date = 1994-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Seybold successes: New York move; melds print, new media| work = The Cole Papers| accessdate = 2010-05-23| date = May 1997| url = http://www.colepapers.net/TCP.archive/Cole_Papers_97/TCP_97_05/seybold.HTML}}</ref> The web became a dominant concern in May 1995.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Cole| first = David| title = Web discussions dominate 15th annual Seybold Seminars| work = The Cole Papers| accessdate = 2011-07-09| date = May 1995| url = http://www.colepapers.net/TCP.Archive/Cole_Papers_95/TCP_95_05/seybold.html}}</ref>
The events have been hailed as "milestones for designers, developers, and production folks of all stripes in their struggle to understand what is going on with the technology"<ref>{{Cite web| last = Black| first = Roger| title = The view out the side windows is getting a bit blurry| work = Roger Black| accessdate = 2010-05-23| date = 2006-10-13| url = http://www.rogerblack.com/blog/view_getting_blurry}}</ref> and as "must-attend venues where all of the most important announcements about desktop publishing, computerized print production, and, eventually, Web-based publishing routinely were made."<ref>{{Cite web| last = Henry| first = Patrick| title = 1996 Is Calling, and So Is Seybold San Francisco| work = Print CEO| accessdate = 2010-06-07| date = 2008-07-08| url = http://printceo.com/2008/07/1996-is-calling-and-so-is-seybold-san-francisco}}</ref>
[[Craig Cline]] served as vice president of content development for the Seminars.<ref>{{Cite web| title = About Us| work = Seybold Seminars| accessdate = 2010-05-23| year = 1997| url = http://www.seyboldseminars.com/News/about_us.html |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/19970801155434/http://www.seyboldseminars.com/News/about_us.html |archivedate = 1997-08-01}}</ref>
Attendance began to decline in 2001<ref>{{Cite news| title = Seybold Seminars Boston 2001: Adobe Systems’ new-product announcements stole the publishing show| first=Robin| last=Peek| work = Information Today| accessdate = 2010-05-23| date = June 2001| url = http://www.infotoday.com/IT/jun01/peek.htm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Seybold Carries On: Crowds Are Smaller, Exhibitors Are Fewer, But Conference Still Draws Many| first=Mathew| last=Honan| work = Macworld| accessdate = 2010-06-11| date = 2001-09-27| url = http://www.macworld.com/article/2434/2001/09/27seybold.html}}</ref> and continued to slide until the event was discontinued in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Seybold Seminars No More: The End of an Era| work = Creative Pro| accessdate = 2010-05-23| date = 2005-10-05| url = http://www.creativepro.com/article/seybold-seminars-no-more-the-end-of-an-era}}</ref>
